revision.text:
{{Christian Eschatology}} The '''abomination of desolation,''' '''abomination that makes desolate''', or '''desolating sacrilege''' (Hebrew: {{Lang-he-n|הַשִּׁקּוּץ מְשׁוֹמֵֽם}}, ''ha-shikkuts meshomem'')<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://biblehub.com/interlinear/daniel/11-31.htm|title=Daniel 11:31 — Interlinear Bible|last=|first=|date=|website=Biblehub|access-date=}}</ref> is a term found in the [[Book of Daniel]] which means literally "an abomination that desolates" or "an abomination that appalls".<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.biblestudytools.com/dictionaries/bakers-evangelical-dictionary/the-abomination-that-causes-desolation.html|chapter=Abomination That Causes Desolation, the|title=Baker's Evangelical Dictionary of Biblical Theology Online|website=Bible Study Tools}}</ref>
==Etymology== {{See also|Abomination (Bible)}} The word "abomination" is described as a "detestable act" or "detestable thing"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://biblehub.com/hebrew/8441.htm|title=Strong's Hebrew: 8441. תּוֹעֵבָה (toebah) -- abomination|website=biblehub.com}}</ref> and in both [[Biblical Hebrew|biblical]] and [[Mishnaic Hebrew|rabbinic Hebrew]], is a familiar term for an [[cult image|idol]],<ref>I Kings, xi. 5; II Kings, xxiii. 13; Sifra, Ḳedoshim, beginning, and Mekilta, Mishpatim, xx. ed. Weiss, 107.</ref> or pertains to idolatrous worship, and therefore may well have the same application in Daniel, which should accordingly be rendered, in agreement with {{bibleref2|Ezra|9:1-4}} "motionless abomination" or, also, "appalling abomination".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/353-abomination-of-desolation|title=Abomination of Desolation - Jewish Encyclopedia|work=jewishencyclopedia.com}}</ref> Some scholars—Hoffmann, Nestle, Bevan, and others—suggest that as a designation for [[Jupiter (mythology)|Jupiter]] it is simply an intentional perversion of his usual appellation "''[[Baalshamin|Baal Shamem]]''" ("lord of heaven") is quite plausible,<ref>Singer, Isidore and Cyrus Adler (Funk and Wagnalls, 1916) The Jewish Encyclopedia: A Descriptive Record of the History, Religion, Literature, and Customs of the Jewish People from the Earliest Times to the Present Day, Volume 1 (page 80)</ref> as attested by the perversion of [[Beelzebub]] into "Βεελζεβούλ" (Greek version) in {{bibleref2|Mark|3:22}}, as well as the express injunction found in Tosef., 'Ab. Zarah, vi. (vii) and Babli 'Ab. Zarah, 46a that the names of idols may be pronounced only in a distorted or abbreviated form.
==Biblical occurrences==
===Daniel=== The phrase "abomination of desolation" ({{Lang-he|הַשִּׁקּ֥וּץ מְשׁוֹמֵם}} ''ha-šiqqūṣ məšōmêm'') is found in three places in the Book of Daniel, all within the literary context of [[apocalyptic literature|apocalyptic]] visions.
{{quote|And he shall make a strong covenant with many for one week; and for half of the week he shall cause sacrifice and offering to cease; and upon the wing of abominations shall come one who makes desolate, until the decreed end is poured out on the desolator.|{{bibleref2|Daniel|9:27|RSV}} ([[Revised Standard Version Catholic Edition|RSV-CE]])}}
{{quote|Forces from him shall appear and profane the temple and fortress, and shall take away the continual burnt offering. And they shall set up the abomination that makes desolate.|{{bibleref2|Daniel|11:31|RSV}} ([[Revised Standard Version Catholic Edition|RSV-CE]])}}
{{quote|And from the time that the continual burnt offering is taken away, and the abomination that makes desolate is set up, there shall be a thousand two hundred and ninety days.|{{bibleref2|Daniel|12:11|RSV}} ([[Revised Standard Version Catholic Edition|RSV-CE]])}}
===Synoptic Gospels=== {{See also|Olivet Discourse}} In the [[Gospel of Matthew]] and the [[Gospel of Mark]], the term ([[Koine Greek|Greek]] τὸ βδέλυγμα τῆς ἐρημώσεως, ''to bdelygma tēs erēmōseōs'') is used by Jesus in the [[Olivet discourse]]. In the Matthean account, Jesus is presented as quoting Daniel explicitly. In the [[Gospel of Mark]], the phrase "spoken of by Daniel the prophet" is absent in the [[Codex Sinaiticus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sinaiticus.com/|title=Codex Sinaiticus in English Anderson Translation|website=www.sinaiticus.com}}</ref>
{{quote|So when you see the desolating sacrilege spoken of by the prophet Daniel, standing in the holy place (let the reader understand), then let those who are in Judea flee to the mountains.|{{bibleref2|Matthew|24:15-16|RSV}} ([[Revised Standard Version Catholic Edition|RSV-CE]])}}
{{quote|But when you see the desolating sacrilege set up where it ought not to be (let the reader understand), then let those who are in Judea flee to the mountains.|{{bibleref2|Mark|13:14|RSV}} ([[Revised Standard Version Catholic Edition|RSV-CE]])}}
In Luke's version of Jesus' warning, the abomination is not mentioned, and the sign that it is time to flee Jerusalem is explicitly said to be that Jerusalem would be surrounded by armies. {{quote|But when you see Jerusalem surrounded by armies, then know that its desolation has come near. Then let those who are in Judea flee to the mountains, and let those who are inside the city depart, and let not those who are out in the country enter it.|{{bibleref2|Luke|21:20-21|RSV}} ([[Revised Standard Version Catholic Edition|RSV-CE]])}}
==Views==
=== Historicism === {{See also|Historicism (Christianity)}}
According to Roman historian [[Cassius Dio]], after the Temple was destroyed in 70 AD the worship overseen by the [[Kohen Gadol|High Priest]] ceased.<ref name="biu.ac.il">http://www.biu.ac.il/JS/rennert/history_5.html</ref> The [[Temple Mount]] was covered over with rubble and a pagan temple dedicated to [[Jupiter (mythology)|Jupiter]] was built when [[Hadrian]] became Caesar (117 - 138 AD).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.christusrex.org/www1/jhs/TSsptemp.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-03-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090907043901/http://www.christusrex.org/www1/jhs/TSsptemp.html |archive-date=2009-09-07 |dead-url=yes |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://followinghadrian.com/2014/11/05/exploring-aelia-capitolina-hadrians-jerusalem/|title=Exploring Aelia Capitolina, Hadrian’s Jerusalem|first=|last=followinghadrian|date=5 November 2014|publisher=}}</ref> Hadrian installed on the mount two statues: one of [[Jupiter (god)|Jupiter]] and another of himself; this was seen by the Jews as idolatry. In addition, Hadrian expelled the Jews from Jerusalem altogether, only allowing them into the city on the fast of [[Tisha B'av]] (the ninth day of the lunar month of Av), a day of mourning for the destruction of the First and the Second Jewish Temples. This appears to have caused a [[Bar Kokhba revolt|second Jewish revolt]] with the intent of recapturing Jerusalem and restoring the Temple. In response, Rome sent six full [[Roman legion|legions]] with [[Auxiliaries (Roman military)|auxiliaries]] and elements from up to six additional legions, which finally managed to crush the revolt.<ref name="Israel-Tour-Day">{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110616233531/http://www.rsy-netzer.org.uk/newsletters/mailing-view/65.html|archivedate=16 June 2011|title=Israel Tour Daily Newsletter|url=http://www.rsy-netzer.org.uk/newsletters/mailing-view/65.html|date=27 July 2010}}</ref><ref name="biu.ac.il"/> The temple appears to have been rebuilt during the early [[Umayyad dynasty|Umayyad period]] as the [[al-Aqsa Mosque]], which stands on the site today.<ref>Nicolle, David (1994). Yarmuk AD 636: The Muslim Conquest of Syria. Osprey Publishing.</ref>{{request quotation|date=June 2018}}
====Rabbinical literature==== There is a rabbinical consensus that the expression refers to the 168 BC desecration of the [[Second Temple]] by the erection of a [[Zeus]] statue in its sacred precincts by [[Antiochus IV Epiphanes]] (the flashpoint of the [[Maccabean Revolt]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=353&letter=A|title=Abomination of Desolation - Jewish Encyclopedia|work=jewishencyclopedia.com}}</ref><ref>See [[Apostomus]].</ref> Some rabbis, however, see in it an allusion to [[Manasseh of Judah|Manasseh]], who was reported to have set up "a carved image ... in the house of God".<ref>{{bibleref2|II Chron|33:7}}</ref><ref>Yer. Ta'anit, iv. 68a, and Rashi on the passage in Babli, ibid. 28b.</ref>
====Church Fathers==== [[Church Fathers|Church Father]] [[Augustine of Hippo]] (379) states, "For Luke very clearly bears witness that the prophecy of Daniel was fulfilled when Jerusalem was overthrown." (vol. 6, p.&nbsp;170)
[[John Chrysostom]] understood this to refer to the armies that surrounded Jerusalem and the factions fighting within it which preceded the destruction of the city.<ref name="documentacatholicaomnia.eu">{{cite web|url=http://www.documentacatholicaomnia.eu/04z/z_0345-0407__Iohannes_Chrysostomus__Homilies_on_The_Gospel_Of_Matthew__EN.pdf.html|title=Iohannes Chrysostomus - Homilies on The Gospel Of Matthew [0345-0407] Full Text at Documenta Catholica Omnia|website=www.documentacatholicaomnia.eu}}</ref>
====Reformers====
[[John Calvin]] rejects the rabbinical view and wrote "In consequence of the obscurity of this passage it has been twisted in a variety of ways. At the end of the ninth chapter I have shewn the impossibility of its referring to the profanation of the Temple which occurred under the tyranny of Antiochus. On this occasion the angel bears witness to such a complete destruction of the Temple, as to leave no room for the hope of its repair and restoration. Then the circumstances of the time convinces us of this. For he then said, Christ shall confirm the covenant with many for one week, and shall cause the sacrifices and oblation to cease. Afterwards, the abomination that stupifieth shall be added, and desolation or stupor, and then death will distill, says he, upon the astonished or stupefied one. The angel, therefore, there treats of the perpetual devastation of the Temple. So in this passage, without doubt;, he treats of the period after the destruction of the Temple; there could be no hope of restoration, as the law with all its ceremonies would then arrive at its termination" (Commentary on Daniel, vol. 2)
[[John Wesley]] (1754) also rejects the rabbinical view and wrote, "When ye shall see the abomination of desolation - Daniel's term is, 'The abomination that maketh desolate' (xi. 31); that is, the standards of the desolating legions, on which they bear the abominable images of their idols. Standing in the holy place - Not only the temple, and the mountain on which it stood, but the whole city of Jerusalem, and several furlongs of land round about it, were accounted holy; particularly the mountain on which our Lord now sat, and on which the Romans afterward planted their ensigns." <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sacred-texts.com/bib/cmt/wesley/mat024.htm|title=Explanatory Notes on the Whole Bible: Matthew: Matthew Chapter 24|website=www.sacred-texts.com}}</ref>
====Modern biblical scholarship==== {{See also|Book of Daniel#Dating and content|Gospel of Mark#Date}}
Some claim the 1 Maccabees usage of the term pointing to an event prior to the prophecy given by Christ, in the actions of Antiochus IV Epiphanes in the mid-2nd century BC. Specifically, he set up an altar, probably to Zeus or Baal Shamem, in the Second Temple in Jerusalem and sacrificed [[swine]] on it around the year 168 BC.<ref>{{Cite Jewish Encyclopedia |title=Antiochus IV., Epiphanes |url=http://jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/1589-antiochus-iv-epiphanes |last=Ginzberg |first=Louis |volume=1 |page=635}}</ref> Many modern scholars believe that [[Prophecy of Seventy Weeks#Scholarly viewpoint|Daniel 9:27]], 11:31 and 12:11 are examples of ''[[vaticinium ex eventu]]'' ([[Postdiction|prophecies after the event]]) relating to Antiochus.<ref>Ronald S. Wallace, ''The Message of Daniel'', IVP 1979.</ref><ref name="NBD">"Desolating sacrilege" in ''New Bible Dictionary'' (third ed), IVP.</ref>
Most modern scholars <ref>{{cite book | last = McNeile | first = A.H. | authorlink = | title = An Introduction to the Study of the New Testament | publisher = University Press | year = 1927 | location = Oxford | pages = Chap. II part 2 The Synoptic Gospels - 2. Date | url = http://www.katapi.org.uk/NTIntro/SynopGospel2.htm#IVIntEv| doi = | id = | isbn = | nopp = true }}</ref> have concluded that Matthew 24:15 and Mark 13:14 are prophecies after the event about the [[Siege of Jerusalem (70)|siege of Jerusalem in AD 70]] by the Roman general [[Titus]],<ref>Matt 23:37-38; Matt 24:1-2,15-21; Luke 13:34-35; Luke 21:20-21</ref> after the [[First Jewish–Roman War|First Jewish Revolt]], and subsequent destruction of the Jewish Temple.
Some scholars, including Hermann Detering,<ref>{{cite journal|title=The Synoptic Apocalypse (Mark 13 par): A document from the time of Bar Kokhba|journal=Journal of Higher Criticism|date=Fall 2000|first=Hermann|last=Detering|volume=7|issue=2|pages=161–210|id=|url=http://www.radikalkritik.de/Mk13%20JHC.pdf|format=PDF|accessdate=2008-01-14|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080227161050/http://www.radikalkritik.de/Mk13%20JHC.pdf|archivedate=27 February 2008|deadurl=yes|df=}}</ref> see these verses as a ''[[vaticinium ex eventu]]'' about [[Emperor Hadrian]]'s attempt to install the statue of [[Temple of Jupiter Optimus Maximus|Jupiter Capitolinus]] on the site of the ruined Jewish Temple in Jerusalem leading to the [[Bar Kokhba revolt]] of 132-135 AD.
====Preterism==== {{See also|Preterism}} [[Preterism|Preterists]] believe that Jesus quoted this prophecy in Mark 13:14 as referring to an event in his 1st century disciples' immediate future, such as the siege of Jerusalem in 70 AD.<ref>[[Craig Blomberg]], Jesus and the Gospels, Apollos 1997, pp.322-326</ref><ref>[[N. T. Wright]], Jesus and the Victory of God, Fortress 1996, p. 348ff.</ref>
One commentator relates the prophecy to the actions of [[Caligula]] c. 40 AD when he ordered that a golden statue depicting himself as Zeus [[incarnate]] be set up in the Temple in Jerusalem.<ref>Harvard University Press, 1976, {{ISBN|0-674-39731-2}}, ''The Crisis Under Gaius Caligula'', pages 254-256:</ref> This prospect however, never came to fruition since he was assassinated in 41 AD along with his wife and daughter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usask.ca/antiquities/coins/caligula.html|title=Coins of the Emperor Caligula|date=17 February 2001|publisher=|deadurl=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010217055505/http://www.usask.ca/antiquities/coins/caligula.html|archivedate=17 February 2001|df=}}</ref>
====Christocentric interpretation==== Some, such as Peter Bolt, head of New Testament at [[Moore Theological College]], claim that the abomination of desolation in [[Mark 13]] refers to the crucifixion of the Son of God; in other words, Jesus is referring to his own impending death.<ref>Peter G. Bolt, The Cross from a Distance: Atonement in Mark’s Gospel, New Studies in Biblical Theology, 18. Downers Grove: InterVarsity, 2004.</ref>
In his book, Discourses in Matthew, Lutheran theologian and professor of Systematic Theology and New Testament at [[Concordia Theological Seminary]], Dr. David. P. Scaer, states,
{{quote|Within the context of the Fifth Discourse, which focuses on Jesus' death and Jerusalem's destruction, the best explanation for "the desolating sacrilege ... standing in the holy place" is the crucifixion of Jesus at Golgotha (27:33). He is the "desolating sacrilege" and Golgotha is "the holy place".<ref>David P. Scaer, Discourses in Matthew: Jesus Teaches the Church (St. Louis, MO., Concordia Publishing House, 2004), 382</ref>}}
===Futurism=== {{see also|Futurism (Christianity)}} Interpreters with a [[Futurism (Christianity)|futurist]] perspective think that Jesus' prophecy deals with a literal, [[end-time]]s [[False Prophet]].<ref>King James Bible 1620, Revelation 16:13,19:20,20:10</ref> Futurists consider the abomination of desolation prophecy of Daniel mentioned by Jesus in Matthew 24:15 and Mark 13:14 to refer to an event in the future, when there appears "[[Man of Sin|the man of lawlessness]]".<ref>King James Bible 1620 Revelation 16:13, 19:20, 20:10</ref>{{Citation needed|date=October 2012}}
[[Premillennialism|Premillennialist]] futurists like [[Arthur Pink]] in his work ''The Antichrist'' <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biblebelievers.com/Pink/antichrist08.htm|title=The Antichrist|publisher=biblebelievers.com|year=1923|author=Pink, Arthur W.|pages=Chapter 6, The Career of the Antichrist|accessdate=2007-06-25| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070707224515/http://www.biblebelievers.com/Pink/antichrist08.htm| archivedate= 7 July 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> attribute vast portions within the Old and New Testament to this future figure that will rise to global prominence politically, economically and militarily by setting up a governmental structure possessing sweeping powers over worship and the affairs of humanity.
===Mixed interpretation===
====Multiple fulfillments==== Methodist theologian [[Adam Clarke]] and Anglican bishop [[Thomas Newton]] interpret the abomination of desolation as a proverbial phrase that could include multiple events "substituted in the place of, or set up in opposition to, the ordinances of God, his worship, his truth, etc."<ref name="sacred-texts">{{cite web|url=http://www.sacred-texts.com/bib/cmt/clarke/dan012.htm|title=Commentary on the Bible by Adam Clarke: Daniel: Daniel Chapter 12|work=sacred-texts.com}}</ref> This allows for some or all of the examples in the following (incomplete) list to be viewed as partial fulfillments of this prophecy simultaneously:{{citation needed|date=January 2013}}
* the re-dedication of the Temple to Zeus by Antiochus IV Epiphanes in 167 BC, * the worship of the Roman Standards on the [[Temple Mount]] under Titus in 70 AD and * the building of the [[Dome of the Rock]] by the [[Umayyad Caliph]] [[Abd al-Malik ibn Marwan]] in 691 AD.
====The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints==== The [[Joseph Smith–Matthew]] states (in verse 12) that the abomination of desolation spoken of by Daniel is the destruction of Jerusalem (first in AD 70). Later (in verse 32) it states that the abomination of desolation will be fulfilled again when at the end times, when Jerusalem is subject to much destruction before the [[Second Coming]] of Christ.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lds.org/scriptures/bd/abomination-of-desolation?lang=eng|title=Bible Dictionary: Abomination of Desolation|publisher=Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints|accessdate=2011-12-15}}</ref>
